ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Unfortunately, the occurrence of a suspected case of paralytic polio in a displaced person camp with Syrian refugees outside of Syria is not totally a surprise. History elsewhere has shown that displaced persons coming from areas of civil unrest where routine health infrastructures have been disrupted and vaccination activities have been significantly impacted, can be exporters/importers of communicable diseases, especially vaccine preventable diseases. A recent case in point was the outbreak in the Horn of Africa involving Somalia, and displaced persons camps with Somali refugees in Kenya and Ethiopia.

In the case of polio, for every 1 paralytic case, there are an average of 200 "silently" infected individuals without paralytic manifestations. Hence, it is easy to understand how the virus can travel from one location to another virtually undetected. In the case of the Middle East countries, there is evidence that WPV1 has been circulating since late 2012 when Egypt identified a WPV1 in environmental samples (sewage samples), documenting that some one (or individuals) had a WPV1 infection and the virus was being excreted into the sewage samples (see Poliomyelitis - worldwide (01): Egypt ex Pakistan, Niger 20130122.1509210). From February 2013 through February 2014, there have been multiple samples of WPV1 isolated from environmental samples throughout Israel, starting in the south and moving northward, yet no paralytic cases associated with a WPV1 infection have been identified.

A positive sign in the region is that acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) surveillance is ongoing. It is possible that this current suspected case is due to a non-poliovirus AFP event, and the press coverage a result of heightened awareness of the possible threat outside of Syria. Obviously we await results of the laboratory testing by the reference laboratory in Cairo.

Looking at the global picture, in the approximately one month since the last ProMED-mail global update (Poliomyelitis - update (02): Afghanistan, global 20140215.2271839), the number of confirmed cases have more than doubled, from 11 to 28. The very good news contained in the weekly highlights is the concerted effort to involve religious leaders in promoting vaccination activities, especially in geographic areas where community leaders have taken a religious bias stand against vaccination. Hopefully this will lead to a renewed acceptance of vaccinations and the cessation of violence against vaccinators in these communities.

For a map showing the locations of confirmed cases of WPV infections worldwide as of 4 Mar 2014, see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Poliocasesworldwide.aspx. - Mod.MPP]
